msContents.summary: A copy of Ælfric 's Grammar and Glossary, produced in Exeter in the late eleventh century.

msItem.author: Ælfric
msItem.title: Grammar
msItem.incipit: 2r Ego Ælfricus ut minus sapiens has excerptiones de prisciano minore uel maiore uobis puerulis tenellis ad uram linguam transferre studui
2v Ic ælfric ƿolde þas lytlan boc aƿendan to engliscum gereorde of þam stæf cræfte þe ys ge haten grammatica
msItem.explicit: 93v On leden sprete mænig fealde ge tel acon englise nis nan þæra ge ƿunelic buton þrianum libra onleden ys ƿund onenglise Fif penegas ge macigað ænne scillingc ˥ [xxx] penega ænne mancs

msItem.author: Ælfric
msItem.title: Glossary
msItem.rubric: 93v Incipiunt glosule multarum rerum anglice exposite a quodam sapientiae
msItem.incipit: 93v Deus omnipotens þæt is god ælmihtig. Be ƿæs æfre unbegunnen. ˥ æfre beoð unge endod
msItem.explicit: 93v Guttur · þrotu · mentum · cynn barba beard . (ends imperfectly)

collation.p:
The MS consists of twelve quires as follows:
1 modern paper flyleaf
6 paper flyleaves (fols. i-vi)
Quire 1:8, wanting first leaf, probably blank (fols. 1-7)
Quires 2-11:8 (fols. 8-87)
Quire 12:8, wanting leaves 7 and 8 after fol. 93 (fols. 88-93)
2 paper flyleaves (fols. vii-viii)
collation.catchwords: Early modern catchwords in pencil are found in the lower margin of the last verso in each quire except the first.

foliation.p: Foliated in pen and pencil in the upper right corner of each page. The first modern paper flyleaf is unfoliated.

condition.p: The manuscript contained 290 pages (145 leaves) in 1574, i.e., 52 leaves more than at present; and Ælfric's Glossary was followed by 'Historia Angliæ Saxon'. See the printed list of Parker's donation to the University, found in some copies of his De antiquitate Britannicæ Ecclesiæ Cantuariensis (1572).

The last two leaves of Quire 12, now wanting, were present in the 16th century when John Joscelyn (1529-1603) Joscelyn, John, 1529-1603 included words excerpted from them in London, Lambeth Palace 692, fols 9v-10r.
A piece of parchment (5 cm x 1.5 cm) has been cut from the outer top corner of fol. 1.
Moderate cropping presumably occurred on the occasion of the earlier binding, as ink foliation numbers and the 17th-century annotations have suffered.

layout.p: Ruled in dry point for 26 (quires 7-12) or 27 lines (quires 1-6). Ruling varies in quire 6: 23 lines on leaves 3-6 (fols. 42-45), 25 lines on leaves 2 and 7 (fols. 41 and 46) and 27 lines on leaves 1 and 8 (fols. 40 and 47).
As prickings exist only in the outer margins of the manuscript, the leaves were pricked before folding.

handDesc.p: The main text of the book is written in five hands 'carefully differentiating Latin and OE by their use of Caroline or Insular minuscule respectively' (Drage 1978, p. 337).
For more details on the hands, see the description available at The Production and Use of English Manuscripts 1060-1220 project.

list.head: Marginalia
list.item: Marginalia throughout in the hand of Robert Talbot (d. 1558), showing a special interest in place-names. His note on fol. 93v, Vide librum de legibus anglorum et danorum refers probably to CCCC MS 383, which he possessed or at least used.
Other marginalia are by John Joscelyn (1529-1603) Joscelyn, John, 1529-1603 . See, for example, the marginalia on fol. 11r where the larger hand is Talbot and the smaller one Joscelyn.
On fol. 41v there is a marginal annotation by Matthew Parker.

bindingDesc.p: Plain light brown leather binding by Douglas Cockerell (1969) with gold lettering on spine.

The previous binding, as noted by N.R. Ker, dated from the 18th century. The current binding incorporates the pastedown from an earlier binding, being a page from Paulus de Sancta Maria, bishop of Burgos, Scrutinum Scripturarum (Paris, Anthonius Bonne Mere, colophon is dated 1472; but it was actually printed c. 1515). It also has the CUL bookplate, with number '5412'.
There are binding strips or guards around every quire, with leaf 8 of Quire 1 (fol. 7) and leaf 1 of Quire 12 (fol. 88) attached by them.

history.provenance: Ker ascribes a Christ Church, Canterbury provenance based on the suggestion that it was bound with London, British Library, MS Cotton Domitian A.viii, an assertion that has been refuted by Dumville. Drage suggests that although the manuscript is not identifiable in the inventories of 1327 or 1506, it remained at Exeter until the sixteenth century (p. 338). It was owned by Matthew Parker (1504-1575) Parker, Matthew, 1504-1575 , Archbishop of Canterbury.
history.acquisition: It was given to the University Library by Matthew Parker (1504-1575) Parker, Matthew, 1504-1575 in 1574. It appears as no. 23 in the list of his gifts, 'Libri scripti'.
